# Core Objective

Design the best system for:

## 1. Objective validation

Use deterministic rules to detect:

- date logic errors
- prize pool math errors
- missing mandatory sections
- state/permit mismatches
- invalid structural combinations
- builder-to-terms mismatches
- inconsistencies in counts, values, dates, ages, or locations

---

## 2. Qualitative review

Use AI to detect:

- ambiguous wording
- vague prize descriptions
- duplicated wording
- contradictory clauses
- operational impracticality
- drafting weakness
- risky discretion wording
- missing nuance for special prize types
- readability and legal-style issues

---

## 3. Scoring

Generate:

- overall score out of 100
- weighted category scores
- risk band
- readiness status

---

# Hybrid Architecture Requirement

The system must use a layered model.

## Layer 1 — Deterministic Rules Engine

Examples:

- draw date must occur after promotion close date
- unclaimed draw must occur after original draw
- total prize pool must equal prize count × value
- if travel prize exists → travel clause must exist
- if entrants under 18 allowed → guardian clause required
- if instant win promotion → draw clause must not exist
- if promotion operates in SA/ACT → permit placeholders required
- if publication required → publication clause required

---

## Layer 2 — Clause Extraction / Classification

Identify sections such as:

- promoter
- eligibility
- entry mechanics
- draw mechanics
- prize description
- travel conditions
- notification
- publication
- unclaimed prizes
- privacy
- liability

---

## Layer 3 — AI Review

AI should review:

- ambiguity
- contradictions
- missing nuance
- operational weaknesses
- drafting quality
- unclear prize descriptions

---

## Layer 4 — Score Aggregation

Combine rule results and AI review into final score.

